    <h2>Boronia — Dandenong Ranges Foothills, Cold Easterly Winters, High Wood Heating Demand</h2>
    <div class="local-box"><p>Boronia sits at the foot of the Dandenong Ranges, and its position directly facing the eastern ranges makes it one of the colder eastern suburbs in Melbourne's metropolitan area. The suburb developed through the 1950s, 1960s and 1970s, and its housing stock — predominantly solid brick veneer on generous blocks — reflects a period when open fireplaces and solid fuel heaters were standard in new construction. The combination of cold winters, high heating demand and an ageing housing stock creates a suburb where professional chimney maintenance is genuinely important, not just a periodic nicety. Boronia experiences a significantly colder winter climate than the flat suburbs to its west. Cold air drainage from the Dandenong Ranges feeds directly into the suburb on still nights, and the suburb regularly records temperatures three to five degrees below what Knox's western suburbs experience. Winter mornings can be bitterly cold, with ground frosts persisting on shadier sections of the suburb well into the day. Wood fires are typically lit in Boronia from early April through to late October — a longer heating season than most comparable suburbs. With 50-plus years of heavy seasonal use, many Boronia chimneys have significant creosote deposits, and older brick stacks often show mortar deterioration that needs attention. Properties backing onto the Dandenong Foothills Park or the Rangeview area also experience frequent bird nesting in chimneys through the warmer months. We service Boronia regularly as part of our Dandenong Ranges foothills run.</p></div>
